<TITLE> China lawmakers to review cabinet reorganisation bill </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Feb 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A proposal to streamline China's central government will be presented for approval at the National People's Congress, or parliament, during its annual session next week, state radio said on Wednesday. No other details about the proposal were disclosed, but local media have reported several clusters of ministries will be consolidated into "super-ministries" to try to reduce bureaucratic overlap and boost efficiency. State media had previously said the just concluded three-day session of the Party's elite 204-member Central Committee would discuss personnel changes and plans to restructure the cabinet. China's political system needed improvements to keep pace with the requirements of the country's economic and social development, the protection of democratic rights and social fairness and justice, the Central Committee said in a statement issued by Xinhua after the session. Some sources have said a super ministry merging the banking, securities and insurance regulators may be announced, and the official Xinhua news agency has reported the Ministry of Agriculture, Ministry of Water Resources and State Forestry Administration will be merged. Others could include a consolidation of the energy and transport sectors into two coherent bodies. President Hu Jintao will be looking for a show of unity, with members backing these potentially divisive changes, which Xinhua has said could see the number of cabinet agencies reduced to 21 from 
